<HEAD>Writers Receive `Edgar' Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist Hillary Waugh was named Thursday a
Grand Master among mystery writers as the 1989 Edgar Allan Poe
Awards were given out by the Mystery Writers of America Inc. in a
ceremony at a Manhattan hotel.
   Edgar winners in other categories are as follows:
   Best Novel: ``A Cold Red Sunrise,'' by Stuart M. Kaminski.
   Best First Novel By An American Author: ``Carolina Skeletons,''
by David Stout.
   Best Original Paperback: ``The Telling of Lies,'' by Timothy
Findley.
   Best Fact Crime: ``In Broad Daylight,'' by Harry N. MacLean.
   Best Critical-Biographical Work: ``First You Dream, Then You
Die: Cornell Woolrich,'' by Francis M. Nevins Jr.
   Best Young Adult Novel: ``Incident At Loring Groves,'' by Sonia
Levitin.
   Best Juvenile Mystery: ``Megan's Island,'' by Willow David
Roberts.
   Best Short Story: ``Flicks,'' by Bill Crenshaw.
   Best Episode In A TV Series: ``The Devil's Foot,'' by Gary
Hopkins.
   Best Television Feature: ``Man Against the Mob,'' by David J.
Kinghorn.
   Best Motion Picture: ``The Thin Blue Line,'' no author.
   The Ellery Queen Award: Richard Levinson (posthumously).
   The Ellery Queen award: William Link.
   Special Theater Award: ``Sheer Madness.''
   The Robert Fish Award (Short Story): ``Different Drummers,'' by
Linda Johnson.
</TEXT>
